</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="91" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Biology and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
Two males and three females were collected during mid May, 2018. All were collected at ultraviolet lights over two nights in a Nu Jiang (Salween) river valley in the northwestern part of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="China’s">China's</normalizedToken>
Yunnan Province bordering North Myanmar (Kachin State). The new species was collected at altitudes of approximately 2100 meters in mixed mountain forest, dominated by various deciduous trees, bamboo and bushes (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 21, 22" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21, 22. Type locality of T. (Vestiplex) butvilai sp. nov., China, NW. Yunnan, Nu Jiang valley, S. from Gongshan, 27 ° 43.42 ' N, 98 ° 45.15 ' E." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.869.34166.figures21-22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/323076" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Figs 21-22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="91" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tipulidae" genus="Tipula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tipula (V.) butvilai" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="butvilai" subGenus="V.">Tipula (V.) butvilai</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., is closest to 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. (V.) testata" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="testata" subGenus="V.">T. (V.) testata</taxonomicName>
(China, Sichuan) based on the shape of the male hypopygium. Both species are characterized by their hypertrophied ventral portion of tergite 9 and a pair of lobes on posterior margin of dorsal portion of tergite 9 but can be easily separated by the shape of the appendage of sternite 9, inner gonostylus and details of tergite 9. They can also be separated by the yellow preapical ring on the femur which is present in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. (V.) butvilai" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="butvilai" subGenus="V.">T. (V.) butvilai</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., but absent in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. (V.) testata" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="testata" subGenus="V.">T. (V.) testata</taxonomicName>
. Other species closely related to 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. (V.) butvilai" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="butvilai" subGenus="V.">T. (V.) butvilai</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., and 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. (V.) testata" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="testata" subGenus="V.">T. (V.) testata</taxonomicName>
are 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. (V.) bicornigera" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="bicornigera" subGenus="V.">T. (V.) bicornigera</taxonomicName>
(Taiwan; 
<bibRefCitation author="Alexander, CP" journalOrPublisher="Philippine Journal of Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="93 - 134" refId="B6" refString="Alexander, CP, 1938a. New or little-known Tipulidae from eastern Asia (Diptera). XXXVI. . Philippine Journal of Science 66: 93 - 134" title="New or little-known Tipulidae from eastern Asia (Diptera). XXXVI." volume="66" year="1938 a">Alexander 1938a</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 2, fig. 26), 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. (V.) subtestata" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="subtestata" subGenus="V.">T. (V.) subtestata</taxonomicName>
(China, Sichuan; 
<bibRefCitation author="Alexander, CP" journalOrPublisher="Philippine Journal of Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="439 - 478" refId="B7" refString="Alexander, CP, 1938b. New or little-known Tipulidae from eastern Asia (Diptera). XXXIX. . Philippine Journal of Science 66: 439 - 478" title="New or little-known Tipulidae from eastern Asia (Diptera). XXXIX." volume="66" year="1938 b">Alexander 1938b</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 2, fig. 30) and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tipulidae" genus="Tipula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tipula (Vestiplex) xingshana" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xingshana" subGenus="Vestiplex">Tipula (Vestiplex) xingshana</taxonomicName>
Yang &amp; Yang, 1997(China, Hubei; 
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="91" refId="B24">Yang and Yang 1997</bibRefCitation>
, p. 1438, fig. 3
<normalizedToken originalValue="a–c">a-c</normalizedToken>
) which all share a hypertrophied ventral portion of tergite 9, but can be separated by the shape of posterior margin of the dorsal portion of tergite 9, which includes two pairs of lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="91" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
The new species is named after our colleague and prominent Lithuanian collector Rimantas Butvila (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Joniškis">Joniskis</normalizedToken>
, Lithuania).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
